items.abstract: <jats:p><jats:italic>ICB-1</jats:italic> chromosome 1 open reading frame 38 (C1orf38) is a human gene initially described by our group to be involved in differentiation processes of cancer cells. Recently, we have reported <jats:italic>ICB-1</jats:italic> as a novel estrogen target gene and identified an estrogen response element in its promoter. In this study, we examined the role of <jats:italic>ICB-1</jats:italic> in regulation of proliferation of breast and ovarian cancer cells. We knocked down its expression in estrogen-dependent MCF-7 breast cancer cells and hormone-unresponsive SK-OV-3 ovarian cancer cells by stable transfection with a specific shRNA plasmid followed by G-418 selection. Knockdown of <jats:italic>ICB-1</jats:italic> enabled a considerable estrogen response of SK-OV-3 cells in terms of proliferation. This transformation of SK-OV-3 cells into an estrogen-responsive phenotype was accompanied by upregulation of estrogen receptor α (ERα) expression and a significant decrease of ERβ expression on the mRNA level. Expression of ERα-dependent genes progesterone receptor, <jats:italic>pS2</jats:italic>, <jats:italic>fibulin 1c</jats:italic>, and <jats:italic>c-fos</jats:italic> was elevated in SK-OV-3 cells stably expressing <jats:italic>ICB-1</jats:italic> shRNA. In MCF-7 cells, <jats:italic>ICB-1</jats:italic> knockdown exerted similar effects on gene expression, supporting a general role of <jats:italic>ICB-1</jats:italic> in estrogen responsiveness. Our data suggest that differentiation-associated gene <jats:italic>ICB-1</jats:italic> might exert antagonistic actions on cellular estrogen response, which can result in inhibition of estradiol-triggered proliferation. The molecular mechanisms mediating this inhibitory effect of <jats:italic>ICB-1</jats:italic> on estrogen signaling are suggested to be limitation of ERα transcript levels but sustaining high levels of ERβ, reducing both activation of ERα target genes and cellular proliferation. The identification of <jats:italic>ICB-1</jats:italic> as a new player in endocrine-related cancer encourages further studies on the significance of this gene in cancer development and therapy.</jats:p>
